  "prompt": "What is the oxidation number of nitrogen?",
  "response": "The oxidation number of nitrogen can vary depending on the compound it is in. Nitrogen can display a range of oxidation states from -3 to +5. Here are some common oxidation states of nitrogen in various compounds:\n\n- Nitrogen in ammonia (NH\u2083) has an oxidation number of -3.\n- Nitrogen in dinitrogen (N\u2082) has an oxidation number of 0.\n- Nitrogen in nitrogen dioxide (NO\u2082) has an oxidation number of +4.\n- Nitrogen in nitrate (NO\u2083\u207b) has an oxidation number of +5.\n- Nitrogen in nitrite (NO\u2082\u207b) has an oxidation number of +3.\n- Nitrogen in nitric oxide (NO) has an oxidation number of +2.\n\nThe specific oxidation state of nitrogen in a compound depends on the chemical context and the nature of the atoms it is bonded to.",
